This lab will introduce the basics of creating interactive, web-based apps using R Shiny. This lab is not graded, as it is rather meant to serve as a resource for your data science career (and may be helpful on your final project!).

Shiny?

Shiny is an R package used to build web-based apps with R in RStudio. Shiny can incorporate CSS themes and JavaScript actions. To see some existing apps in action, check out the Shiny Gallery linked here. Once created, you can easily share your app with others! You can upload it to shinyapps.io, which allows you to create and publish your app. With a free account, you get 5 active applications, with 25 hours per month of active use.

To create a Shiny app, instead of coding in an .Rmd file (markdown), we will code using an R script (.R) file. Note that you may have to install the package using

install.packages("shiny")

To create a new Shiny App, go to File > New File > Shiny Web App and follow the on-screen prompts. Make sure to keep the option Single File (app.R) selected. You should see that the file app.R will open – click on Run App to see the result.

Some examples are included in the shiny package. Enter any of the following code in the Console to see the app in action (along with the code):

runExample("01_hello")        # a histogram
runExample("02_text")         # tables and data frames
runExample("03_reactivity")   # a reactive expression
runExample("04_mpg")          # global variables
runExample("05_sliders")      # slider bars
runExample("06_tabsets")      # tabbed panels
runExample("07_widgets")      # help text and submit buttons
runExample("08_html")         # Shiny app built from HTML
runExample("09_upload")       # file upload wizard
runExample("10_download")     # file download wizard
runExample("11_timer")        # an automated timer

There are a few basic components in a Shiny app, the user-interface, which specifies what the user experiences, the server logic, which gives the behind- the-scenes operations, and a function to build and run the application:

library(shiny)

# Define UI:
ui <- fluidPage(
  
)

# Define server logic
server <- function(input, output){
  
}

# Build and run the application
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

The fluidPage() function creates a dynamic HTML user interface that you see when you look at an app. The server() function contains the R commands your computer (or external server) uses to run the app. Finally, the function shinyApp() builds the app based on the user interface and server code.

Building a Shiny app

We’re going to build an app that allows users to explore the Brexit referendum poll outcomes for 127 polls conducted between January 2016 to June 23. The data are available in the dslabs package and can be loaded with the code data("brexit_polls") once the package is installed. We will build the app using the following two steps:

  • First, we’ll construct the UI, focusing on the widgets and layout design
  • Next, we’ll learn how to connect the input widgets and outputs with the code by using the server function
  • And finally, we’ll run the app itself

User interface: inputs

The user inputs essentially collect values from the user. These can be any sort of data – continuous, categorical, dates, etc. These inputs are added as widgets to the Shiny app, and most input widgets are set-up as

___Input(inputId, label, ...)

or

___Button(inputId, label, ...)

For instance, to create a slider widget labeled “Number of bins” that controls the number of bins, ranging from 1 to 50, we can use the following code:

sliderInput(inputId = "bins", label = "Number of bins:",
            min = 1, max = 50, value = 30)

This code creates the following input:

Notice the inputId. This tells Shiny what this input widget is named, and will be important when connecting it to the server code later. This name is not seen by the end-user, but the label is.

Examples of input widgets are given below. The first and second arguments of the function will always be inputId and label, but the remaining arguments depend on what exactly is being inputed. For further details, consult the help documentation.

Note that if you run the sliderInput code in the Console directly, you will actually see some HTML code!

Let’s take a look at some more input widgets and what they correspond to on the user’s side. Note that you can add as many widgets as you want/need.

ui <- fluidPage(
  # add slider
  sliderInput("bins", "Number of bins:",
              min = 1, max = 50, value = 30),
  
  # text box input
  textInput("title", "Histogram title", 
            value = "Histogram"),
  
  # combo box
  selectInput("color", "Histogram fill",
              choices = c("Red", "White", "Blue"),
              selected = "Red")
)

server <- function(input, output) {
  
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

User interface: outputs

Just as inputs are added as ___Input(), outputs in Shiny are added with ___Output(). These can be data tables, raw HTML, plots, tables, etc. A table of what each output function creates is below:

Output function Creates
dataTableOutput() data table
htmlOutput() raw HTML
imageOutput() image
plotOutput() plot
tableOutput() table
textOutput() text
uiOutput() raw HTML
verbatimTextOutput() text

Similarly to the inputs, the first argument for each output function is outputId, which is where you specify a name of the output (not seen by the user). Again, this name will serve as a reference when the server() function runs the code.

Note that the output function is still part of the ui that is created. Let’s take a look at an example of an output function that corresponds to the sliderInput() object we created earlier:

ui <- fluidPage(
  # add slider
  sliderInput("bins", "Number of bins:",
              min = 1, max = 50, 
              value = 30),
  
  plotOutput(outputId = "hist")
)

server <- function(input, output) {
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

The code plotOutput(outputId = "hist") allocates space for a plot. However, since we haven’t actually created anything yet, no plot is visible:

Note that each separate input and output is separated by a comma in the fluidPage function, which we will use to create the ui object.

The server function

You may notice that you have a user interface built, but it doesn’t do anything. How was the plot and table in the image created for Exercise 1?

You need to give R commands that react when inputs ar eprovided or are changed. These reactions are seen by updates to the outputs. Take a look at the link given here. As you change the inputs, look at what is highlighted in the server() function below. You will create your own server function to do similar tasks.

The server function plays a special role: it builds a list-like object named output that contains all of the code needed to update the R objects in your app. Each R object needs to have its own entry in the list. You can create an entry by defining a new element for output within the server function. The element name should match the name of the reactive element that you created in the user interface. This is where the inputIds and outputIds that you defined earlier in your ui widgets and outputs come into play.

To create the server() function, follow the three steps below:

  • First, save objects to display to output$<outputId>, where <outputId> is the name given from the ___Output function from earlier. For instance:
server <- function(input, output) { 
  output$hist <- # code
}
  • Next, build these output$<outputId> objects with the render___() family of functions. For instance:
server <- function(input, output) { 
  output$hist <- renderPlot({
    # code to build your object
    # in this case, code to create
    # the histogram
  }) 
}

Each output corresponds to a specific rendering function, given in the following table. Note that each render___ function only requires a single argument: an R expression surrounded by braces. This expression can be one simple line of code, or it can involve many different lines of code.

Render function Creates a reactive
renderDataTable() data table
renderImage() image
renderPlot() plot
renderPrint() version of the given function that captures print output
renderTable() table
renderText() version of the given function to turn its result into a character vector.
renderUI() HTML

The relationship between each output and what “renders” the output is summarized in the graphic below:

  • Finally, access your input values with intput$<inputId>, where <inputId> is the name provided from your ___Input() function from the ui.

Assuming a well-built Shiny app, every time the user moves the slider, selects a value in a combo box, selects a new radio button option, outputs will automatically get updated when inputs change. This is known as reactivity. Reactivity automatically occurs whenever you use an input value to render an output object.

  1. Create a server function that corresponds to the user-interface defined earlier. Use renderPlot() to display a reactive plot that depends on the date range and pollster inputs, and DT::renderDataTable() to display a reactive table that depends on the date range and pollster inputs, sorted by start date.

Solutions

If you’d like to see the ui function and server function as implemented for the Brexit poll example above, you can click on the following button. However, do try to create the app before viewing the solution. As a reminder, the UI and output to be created are given in the following screenshot:

# Define the user interface
ui <- fluidPage(theme = shinytheme("yeti"),
    # Application title
    titlePanel("Brexit Polls Explorer"),
    # sidebar
    sidebarLayout(
        sidebarPanel(
            dateRangeInput(inputId = "daterange",
                           label   = "Enter poll start range",
                           start   = "2016-01-08",
                           end     = "2016-06-23",
                           min     = "2016-01-08",
                           max     = "2016-06-23"),
            selectInput(inputId  = "pollster",
                        label    = "Select pollster",
                        choices  = pollsters)
        ),
        # main panel
        mainPanel(
           plotOutput(outputId = "plotpolls"),
           dataTableOutput(outputId = "tablepolls")
        )
    )
)

# Create server function
server <- function(input, output) {
    output$plotpolls <- renderPlot({
        brexit_polls %>% 
            filter(startdate >= input$daterange[1], 
                   startdate <= input$daterange[2]) %>% 
            filter(pollster == input$pollster) %>% 
            ggplot(aes(x = startdate, y = remain)) +
            geom_point(aes(color = "blue"), size = 2) +
            geom_line(aes(color = "blue")) +
            geom_point(aes(y = leave, color = "red"), size = 2) +
            geom_line(aes(y = leave, color = "red")) +
            labs(x = "Poll's starting date", y = "Proportion") +
            theme_minimal(base_size = 20) +
            theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
            scale_color_identity(name   = "Brexit Decision",
                                 breaks = c("blue", "red"),
                                 labels = c("Remain", "Leave"),
                                 guide  = "legend")
    })
    output$tablepolls <- DT::renderDataTable({
        brexit_polls %>% 
            filter(startdate >= input$daterange[1], 
                   startdate <= input$daterange[2]) %>% 
            filter(pollster == input$pollster) %>% 
            arrange(startdate)
    })
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)
